

a sev1 incident starts at 2am. walk through the correct response order.

1. Acknowledge and assess severity
2. open war room in slack
3. assign an incident commander to own communication
4. mitigation - rollback/failover/scale
5. communicate status
6. root cause
7. resolution
8. post mortem

mitigate first, do root cause analysis later (probably not at 2am). 

1) ack page
2) assess severity, declare sev1 if prod is down
3) open a bridge in zoom/slack
4) mitigation - rollback, failover, scale, kill a bad / stuck job
5) communication with stakeholders every 15-30 minutes
6) once stable look for root cause
7) resolve the page
8) blameless postmortem, identify action items


SLO, SLA, SLI

SLA is your agreement or contract with your customer
SLO are the objectives you want to meet or exceed over a number of days, responsiveness, etc.
SLI service level indicators - 4 golden signals - latency, errors, saturation, and traffic... p99 latency or p99 errors? p95 errors? what
is the error budget. alert on % of error budget burn, not 80% cpu or disk 99% full (although those are useful)


SLI is what you measure, SLO is what you aim for, SLA is what you promise. SLOs are your goals for system or application status. 


two of the four golden signals - latency and errors - these make good service level objective grade SLIs. 

use p99 when slow outliers hurt end users. use p50 / p95 when you only care about the typical request. typical request is the
fat part of the performance band, where most latency lives. 


alert on burn rate against your SLO, not a static threshold. 




